---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="ClearIQ — Stakeholder Briefing"
  description="What ClearIQ is, how it got here, and where it is going. Internal briefing for core team and partners."
  noindex={true}
>

<!-- ── Internal Banner ──────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="internal-banner">
  <a href="/" class="banner-logo" aria-label="ClearIQ home">
    <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 28 28" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true">
      <rect width="28" height="28" rx="6" fill="#1A2535"/>
      <text x="14" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Georgia, serif" font-size="14" fill="#1A8EA8">C</text>
    </svg>
    <span class="banner-logo-name">Clear<span class="banner-logo-iq">IQ</span></span>
  </a>
  <span class="banner-badge">Internal · Not Indexed</span>
</div>

<!-- ── Page Header ───────────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="page-header">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="page-kicker">Core Team Briefing</span>
    <h1 class="page-title">What we're building,<br/>how we got here,<br/>and what comes next.</h1>
    <p class="page-sub">
      Written so you can get fully current — without a call.
      This page covers the product, the pivot, the platform, the market, and the team.
      If something is missing or needs updating, reach George directly.
    </p>
    <div class="page-meta">
      <span class="meta-item">Last updated: June 6, 2026</span>
      <span class="meta-divider">·</span>
      <span class="meta-item">George Ngengwe</span>
      <span class="meta-divider">·</span>
      <a href="mailto:gngengwe@gmail.com" class="meta-link">gngengwe@gmail.com</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── Page Body ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
<div class="page-body">
  <div class="container page-layout">

    <!-- Sidebar TOC -->
    <nav class="page-toc" aria-label="Page sections">
      <span class="toc-label">On this page</span>
      <a href="#what-we-build" class="toc-link">What we're building</a>
      <a href="#how-we-got-here" class="toc-link">How we got here</a>
      <a href="#the-platform" class="toc-link">The platform</a>
      <a href="#the-market" class="toc-link">The market</a>
      <a href="#the-team" class="toc-link">The team</a>
      <a href="#where-we-are" class="toc-link">Where we are</a>
      <a href="#whats-next" class="toc-link">What comes next</a>
      <a href="#contact" class="toc-link">Reach George</a>
    </nav>

    <!-- Main content -->
    <div class="page-content">

      <!-- ─── 1. What We're Building ─────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="what-we-build">
        <h2 class="section-h2">What we're building</h2>

        <div class="lede">
          ClearIQ is an authorization and reimbursement platform for OBL owners,
          cardiologists, and the billing teams managing their procedure pipeline.
        </div>

        <p>
          The problem it solves: high-value procedure practices — office-based labs,
          cardiology offices, ambulatory surgery centers — lose a significant portion of
          scheduled revenue because the insurance authorization pipeline is broken.
        </p>

        <p>
          Pre-certification requirements differ by payer, plan, and procedure code.
          Pending authorizations sit for days with no explanation. Denial letters arrive
          in bulk. Appeal letters get written by hand, one at a time, often by billing
          staff who are also managing everything else. Cases that should be recoverable
          simply run out of time.
        </p>

        <p>
          ClearIQ automates the full pipeline — from pre-certification filing through
          denial detection, appeal generation, and reimbursement tracking — so procedures
          stop falling off the schedule before the patient ever walks in.
        </p>

        <div class="highlight-box">
          <p class="highlight-text">
            "I look at Friday's schedule. There are twelve procedures on it.
            By Tuesday morning, sometimes only four make it."
          </p>
          <span class="highlight-attr">— John Lee, MD, OBL Owner</span>
        </div>

        <p>
          That gap — between what a practice schedules and what it actually completes —
          is the problem ClearIQ is built to close. Not by making the appeal process faster,
          but by surfacing authorization gaps early enough that most denials never happen
          in the first place.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 2. How We Got Here ─────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="how-we-got-here">
        <h2 class="section-h2">How we got here</h2>

        <p>
          ClearIQ started as Appeal-IQ — a different product with a different scope
          and a different primary user. The pivot happened after a conversation with
          John Lee on June 6, 2026, and it changed almost everything.
        </p>

        <div class="timeline">

          <div class="timeline-item">
            <div class="tl-marker tl-marker--done"></div>
            <div class="tl-content">
              <span class="tl-date">Early 2026</span>
              <h3 class="tl-heading">Appeal-IQ — the original scope</h3>
              <p class="tl-body">
                The first version was built for attorney-led medical billing appeal teams —
                a workspace for preparing, reviewing, and packaging appeal letters.
                The primary user was assumed to be a legal or compliance professional
                reviewing physician-authored content before submission.
                The product started at post-denial: denial comes in, letter gets written.
              </p>
              <p class="tl-body">
                The landing page was live. The architecture was designed.
                The discovery framework had 27 questions. Things were moving.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="timeline-item">
            <div class="tl-marker tl-marker--pivot"></div>
            <div class="tl-content">
              <span class="tl-date">June 6, 2026</span>
              <h3 class="tl-heading">The conversation with John Lee</h3>
              <p class="tl-body">
                John is a cardiologist who owns and operates an OBL in New York.
                He reached out as a potential investor-client — someone who might use the product
                and also back it. The call was intended to validate Appeal-IQ's existing scope.
                It ended up redefining the entire product.
              </p>
              <p class="tl-body">
                Three things came out of that conversation that weren't on the roadmap:
              </p>
              <ul class="tl-list">
                <li>
                  <strong>The revenue problem starts before the denial.</strong>
                  By the time a denial letter arrives, the appointment window is usually gone.
                  The real problem is pre-authorization — cases that never get authorized
                  don't generate a denial, they just disappear from the schedule.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>The daily user is billing staff, not attorneys.</strong>
                  At John's practice, his office manager Sarah Hudkin manages pre-certs, denials,
                  and appeals alongside everything else she runs.
                  She is not a lawyer. She doesn't have hours to draft letters.
                  She needs automation and visibility, not a document workspace.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>OBLs are the beachhead market.</strong>
                  Cardiologists own their OBLs and feel the revenue impact directly.
                  They have strong incentive to adopt tools that protect procedure revenue.
                  It is a focused, high-value market with a clear decision maker.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="timeline-item">
            <div class="tl-marker tl-marker--now"></div>
            <div class="tl-content">
              <span class="tl-date">June 6, 2026 — Today</span>
              <h3 class="tl-heading">Appeal-IQ → ClearIQ</h3>
              <p class="tl-body">
                The same day as the John conversation, the product was renamed and
                repositioned from the ground up. New scope: the full
                pre-certification-to-reimbursement pipeline. New primary user:
                billing and authorization staff. New beachhead market: OBL owners
                and cardiologists, New York first.
              </p>
              <p class="tl-body">
                The landing page has been rebuilt to reflect the new system —
                nine pipeline steps, a Recovery & Reimbursement Engine, and
                a before/after scenario showing what authorization chaos looks like
                in a real week at a real practice. The internal discovery framework
                has been expanded from 27 to 33 questions to capture new regulatory
                surface from pre-auth scope: BAA obligations, pre-certification
                licensure and agency risk, and False Claims Act implications.
              </p>
              <p class="tl-body">
                The NDA with John's practice, the MVP scope definition with Atabong,
                and the first user session with Sarah are the immediate next steps.
                This is where the work is right now.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 3. The Platform ────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="the-platform">
        <h2 class="section-h2">The platform</h2>

        <p>
          ClearIQ covers the full authorization-to-reimbursement pipeline.
          It is designed to be used by billing and authorization staff as a daily operational tool —
          not a one-time filing assistant. Each step feeds into the next.
        </p>

        <div class="pipeline-grid">
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Pre-Certification Filing</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Pre-cert requests assembled per payer requirements, with required clinical
                documentation identified and attached. Reduces manual lookup across portal documentation.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Auth Status Dashboard</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                All pending authorizations visible in one place — with status, timeline,
                missing actions, and escalation flags. No more portal-by-portal checks.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Denial Detection & Triage</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Denials detected automatically, classified by reason code,
                and routed to the right appeal path — before anyone has to read the letter.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Insurer Coverage Analysis</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Coverage terms, prior auth requirements, and plan-level policy pulled
                per insurer per procedure — so pre-certs are filed with the right documentation the first time.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Clinical Documentation Review</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Medical records assessed against payer criteria.
                Gaps identified before the appeal is written, not after it is rejected again.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">06</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Physician Support Gap Detection</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Missing clinical documentation, unsigned notes, and physician attestation gaps
                surfaced automatically — with specific requests generated for the ordering physician.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">07</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Appeal Letter Generation</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Payer-specific appeal letters generated from the denial reason, clinical record,
                and coverage analysis. Output reviewed by the billing manager before submission.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item">
            <span class="pipeline-num">08</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Appeal Package Builder</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                Full submission package assembled — letter, supporting documentation, physician attestations,
                peer review request — formatted to payer specifications.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="pipeline-item pipeline-item--engine">
            <span class="pipeline-num pipeline-num--engine">09</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="pipeline-heading">Recovery & Reimbursement Engine</h3>
              <p class="pipeline-body">
                After the appeal wins, the engine activates: procedure-level reimbursement tracking,
                appeal ROI by payer and procedure type, remittance reconciliation,
                and a live practice revenue dashboard.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 4. The Market ──────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="the-market">
        <h2 class="section-h2">The market</h2>

        <p>
          The authorization failure problem is not specific to cardiology —
          but OBL owners and cardiologists are the right entry point.
          They own and operate their facilities. They feel the revenue impact directly.
          They have strong motivation to adopt tools that protect procedure throughput,
          and a clear decision-making structure: the physician owner decides,
          the billing manager implements.
        </p>

        <div class="market-grid">
          <div class="market-card market-card--primary">
            <span class="market-badge">Beachhead — Phase 1</span>
            <h3 class="market-heading">OBL Owners & Cardiologists</h3>
            <p class="market-body">
              Office-based labs owned and operated by interventional cardiologists.
              High-value procedures (arterial, venous, cardiac catheterization, EP).
              Authorization failures directly reduce physician income.
              John Lee's New York practice is the first point of contact.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="market-card">
            <span class="market-badge">Phase 2</span>
            <h3 class="market-heading">Ambulatory Surgery Centers</h3>
            <p class="market-body">
              ASCs operate the same authorization bottleneck across a broader procedure mix.
              More complex payer relationships, but the same structural problem.
              Natural expansion from OBL.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="market-card">
            <span class="market-badge">Phase 3</span>
            <h3 class="market-heading">Specialty Practices</h3>
            <p class="market-body">
              GI, pain management, neurosurgery, orthopedics.
              All face prior auth burden on high-value procedures.
              Same pipeline, different procedure codes and payer mix.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="geo-note">
          <span class="geo-label">Geography</span>
          New York first — John Lee's network and NIAC patient population provide initial reach.
          Regional expansion to follow based on payer concentration and OBL density.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 5. The Team ────────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="the-team">
        <h2 class="section-h2">The team</h2>

        <div class="team-grid">

          <div class="team-card">
            <div class="team-avatar team-avatar--george">GN</div>
            <div class="team-info">
              <h3 class="team-name">George Ngengwe</h3>
              <span class="team-role">Product, Strategy, Go-to-Market</span>
              <p class="team-bio">
                Building ClearIQ from product conception through first user.
                Responsible for product design, the discovery and compliance framework,
                stakeholder relationships, and go-to-market. Operating under
                HK Clearway LLC, powered by becomiNG.
              </p>
              <a href="mailto:gngengwe@gmail.com" class="team-contact">gngengwe@gmail.com</a>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="team-card">
            <div class="team-avatar team-avatar--john">JL</div>
            <div class="team-info">
              <h3 class="team-name">John Lee, MD</h3>
              <span class="team-role">Investor-Client · First Point of Contact</span>
              <p class="team-bio">
                Interventional cardiologist and OBL owner in New York.
                John's practice is the first clinical partner — his team is the product's
                intended first user. He brings the domain reality: the schedule, the authorization
                pipeline, the insurer mix, the revenue at stake. He is both advisor and client.
              </p>
              <p class="team-bio">
                His office manager, Sarah Hudkin, is the intended daily user —
                the billing and authorization manager whose workflow ClearIQ is built around.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="team-card">
            <div class="team-avatar team-avatar--atabong">AF</div>
            <div class="team-info">
              <h3 class="team-name">Atabong Fombon</h3>
              <span class="team-role">Engineer</span>
              <p class="team-bio">
                Technical co-builder. Responsible for the application architecture and
                implementation. Working with George to scope and build the MVP around
                the revised platform spec — pre-cert through reimbursement.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="team-card">
            <div class="team-avatar team-avatar--raphael">RN</div>
            <div class="team-info">
              <h3 class="team-name">Raphael Ngengwe</h3>
              <span class="team-role">Physician Consultant</span>
              <p class="team-bio">
                Cardiologist. Independent clinical voice for validating how the platform
                interprets clinical documentation, physician attestations, and medical necessity
                criteria against payer standards.
                Ensures the product speaks accurately to the clinical record.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 6. Where We Are ────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="where-we-are">
        <h2 class="section-h2">Where we are</h2>

        <p>
          ClearIQ is early-stage. The product has been repositioned, the landing page is live,
          the discovery framework is complete, and the first clinical partner is in place.
          Here is what is done and what is not.
        </p>

        <div class="status-table">
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-done"></div>
            <span class="status-item">Product repositioning — Appeal-IQ → ClearIQ</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--done">Done</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-done"></div>
            <span class="status-item">Landing page rebuilt to reflect full pipeline scope</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--done">Done</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-done"></div>
            <span class="status-item">Discovery framework — 33 questions, regulatory and product scope</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--done">Done</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-done"></div>
            <span class="status-item">First clinical partner identified — John Lee, MD (New York OBL)</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--done">Done</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-progress"></div>
            <span class="status-item">NDA / research agreement with John's practice</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--progress">In Progress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-progress"></div>
            <span class="status-item">MVP scope definition with Atabong — pre-cert + appeal core</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--progress">In Progress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-pending"></div>
            <span class="status-item">Business Associate Agreement (BAA) — required before any real PHI</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--pending">Pending</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-pending"></div>
            <span class="status-item">EOB collection from John's practice — calibrates reimbursement engine</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--pending">Pending</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-pending"></div>
            <span class="status-item">First user session — Sarah Hudkin, John's office manager</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--pending">Pending</span>
          </div>
          <div class="status-row">
            <div class="status-indicator status-pending"></div>
            <span class="status-item">MVP application build</span>
            <span class="status-state status-state--pending">Not started</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="discovery-link-block">
          <div class="discovery-link-content">
            <h3 class="discovery-link-heading">The full discovery framework</h3>
            <p class="discovery-link-body">
              The 33-question pre-launch decision framework lives at <code>/discovery</code>.
              It covers regulatory blockers, product scope, legal risk, and what needs to be true
              before ClearIQ works with real patient data. If you are evaluating the platform
              from a compliance or legal angle, that is the right place to start.
            </p>
          </div>
          <a href="/discovery" class="btn-secondary-link">
            View Discovery Framework →
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 7. What Comes Next ─────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="whats-next">
        <h2 class="section-h2">What comes next</h2>

        <p>
          The immediate path is narrow and deliberate. The goal is a working product
          in a real practice, with real authorization data — not a broad launch
          or a wide pilot. Everything between now and first user is about clearing
          the blockers that make that safe and legal.
        </p>

        <ol class="next-steps">
          <li class="next-step">
            <span class="next-step-num">1</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="next-step-heading">Execute the NDA and BAA with John's practice</h3>
              <p class="next-step-body">
                The research NDA covers the observation and workflow analysis phase.
                The BAA is required before ClearIQ processes any pre-authorization or clinical data.
                These are the legal prerequisites for the first user session.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="next-step">
            <span class="next-step-num">2</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="next-step-heading">Collect EOBs from John's practice</h3>
              <p class="next-step-body">
                Explanation of Benefits documents show what insurers are actually paying per procedure,
                per plan, per denial outcome. This data calibrates the reimbursement intelligence engine —
                which payers are most worth appealing, where recovery ROI is highest.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="next-step">
            <span class="next-step-num">3</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="next-step-heading">Scope the MVP with Atabong</h3>
              <p class="next-step-body">
                The MVP covers two pipeline stages: pre-certification filing support and
                denial-to-appeal generation. It does not need to be the full nine-step pipeline
                on day one — it needs to be useful in a real week for Sarah Hudkin.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="next-step">
            <span class="next-step-num">4</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="next-step-heading">First user session</h3>
              <p class="next-step-body">
                A structured research session with Sarah at John's practice —
                observing her current authorization workflow, testing ClearIQ's pre-cert
                and appeal capabilities against real cases, and documenting what the product
                needs to do differently. This is the product-market fit checkpoint.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="next-step">
            <span class="next-step-num">5</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="next-step-heading">Connect with John's NIAC manager</h3>
              <p class="next-step-body">
                John's NIAC patient population represents a specific payer and authorization pattern.
                Understanding how NIAC authorizations behave at his practice shapes
                the pre-cert module's payer-specific logic for the NY market.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <!-- ─── 8. Contact ─────────────────────────────── -->
      <section class="content-section" id="contact">
        <h2 class="section-h2">Reach George</h2>

        <p>
          If you have questions, feedback, or want to discuss any part of the above —
          the fastest path is direct.
        </p>

        <div class="contact-block">
          <div class="contact-row">
            <span class="contact-label">Email</span>
            <a href="mailto:gngengwe@gmail.com" class="contact-value contact-link">gngengwe@gmail.com</a>
          </div>
          <div class="contact-row">
            <span class="contact-label">Phone</span>
            <a href="tel:+18163098526" class="contact-value contact-link">+1 (816) 309-8526</a>
          </div>
